1. Understanding Asymptotic Notation

What is Big O Notation?

Big O notation is a mathematical representation used to measure the efficiency of an algorithm. It describes how the execution time or memory usage grows as the input size increases.

Big O helps developers:

* Analyze and compare different algorithms.
* Predict performance for large datasets.
* Select the most efficient algorithm for a given problem.
* Optimize application performance.

Some common Big O complexities are:

| Complexity | Meaning           |
| ---------- | ----------------- |
| O(1)       | Constant Time     |
| O(log n)   | Logarithmic Time  |
| O(n)       | Linear Time       |
| O(n log n) | Linearithmic Time |
| O(n²)      | Quadratic Time    |

Best, Average, and Worst-Case Scenarios

Linear Search

Best Case:O(1)

Element is found at the first position.
Average Case:O(n/2)≈O(n)

Element is found somewhere in the middle.
Worst Case:O(n)

Element is at the last position or not present.

Binary Search

Best Case:O(1)

Element is found at the middle position.
Average Case:O(log n)

Search space is repeatedly divided into half.
Worst Case:O(log n)
Maximum number of divisions required before finding the element or determining it is absent.

2. Setup

Create a Java project named:

ECommerceSearchSystem

Product Class

public class Product {

    private int productId;
    private String productName;
    private String category;

    public Product(int productId,
                   String productName,
                   String category) {
        this.productId = productId;
        this.productName = productName;
        this.category = category;
    }

    public int getProductId() {
        return productId;
    }

    public String getProductName() {
        return productName;
    }

    public String getCategory() {
        return category;
    }

    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return "Product ID: " + productId +
               ", Product Name: " + productName +
               ", Category: " + category;
    }
}

Implementation

Linear Search Algorithm

Linear search checks each product one by one until the required product is found.

public class LinearSearch {

    public static Product search(Product[] products,
                                 int productId) {

        for (Product product : products) {
            if (product.getProductId() == productId) {
                return product;
            }
        }
        return null;
    }
}

Binary Search Algorithm

Binary search works only on a sorted array. The products are sorted by productId.

public class BinarySearch {

    public static Product search(Product[] products,
                                 int productId) {

        int left = 0;
        int right = products.length - 1;

        while (left <= right) {

            int mid = left + (right - left) / 2;

            if (products[mid].getProductId() == productId) {
                return products[mid];
            }

            if (products[mid].getProductId() < productId) {
                left = mid + 1;
            } else {
                right = mid - 1;
            }
        }

        return null;
    }
}

Main Class

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Product[] products = {
            new Product(101, "Laptop", "Electronics"),
            new Product(102, "Mouse", "Accessories"),
            new Product(103, "Keyboard", "Accessories"),
            new Product(104, "Monitor", "Electronics"),
            new Product(105, "Printer", "Office")
        };

        // Linear Search
        Product linearResult =
                LinearSearch.search(products, 103);

        System.out.println("Linear Search Result:");
        System.out.println(linearResult);

        // Binary Search
        Product binaryResult =
                BinarySearch.search(products, 103);

        System.out.println("\nBinary Search Result:");
        System.out.println(binaryResult);
    }
}

4. Analysis

Time Complexity Comparison

| Operation    | Linear Search | Binary Search |
| ------------ | ------------- | ------------- |
| Best Case    | O(1)          | O(1)          |
| Average Case | O(n)          | O(log n)      |
| Worst Case   | O(n)          | O(log n)      |

Comparison
Linear Search

Advantages:

* Simple to implement.
* Works on both sorted and unsorted data.
* Suitable for small datasets.

Disadvantages:

* Slow for large datasets.
* Requires checking elements one by one.

#### Binary Search

Advantages:

* Much faster for large datasets.
* Reduces search space by half in each iteration.
* Efficient and scalable.

Disadvantages:

* Requires the array to be sorted.
* Slightly more complex to implement.
 Which Algorithm is More Suitable?

For an e-commerce platform, **Binary Search** is more suitable because:

1. E-commerce platforms store thousands or millions of products.
2. Fast search response is essential for a better user experience.
3. Binary search has O(log n) complexity, making it significantly faster than O(n) linear search.
4. Products can be maintained in sorted order based on productId or other searchable attributes.

However, for small or unsorted datasets, linear search can still be useful due to its simplicity.

Conclusion

Linear Search is easy to implement but becomes inefficient as the number of products increases. Binary Search provides much faster search performance with O(log n) time complexity and is therefore the preferred choice for large-scale e-commerce platforms where quick product retrieval is essential.
